<subSubSection id="C31F2DDDBF2DFFD379EFFB71F64CDB58" pageId="26" pageNumber="437" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BBA7E56BF2DFFD379EFFB71F64CDB58" blockId="26.[2034,2620,1174,1592]" lastBlockId="26.[1412,2620,1601,3478]" pageId="26" pageNumber="437">
Phenotypically and ecologically similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C0505D5BF2DFFD37633FA9CF767D823" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1888" box="[2088,2236,1292,1317]" class="Mammalia" family="Canidae" genus="Vulpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="26" pageNumber="437" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrotis">V. macrotis</taxonomicName>
; interbreeding occurs in western 
<collectingRegion id="49C1B0B4BF2DFFD37677FAA3F762D84A" box="[2156,2233,1331,1356]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="26" pageNumber="437">Texas</collectingRegion>
and eastern 
<collectingRegion id="49C1B0B4BF2DFFD3779AFAA3F5EED84A" box="[2433,2613,1331,1356]" country="United States of America" name="New Mexico" pageId="26" pageNumber="437">New Mexico</collectingRegion>
, and some suggest these foxes are conspecific. Both are closely related to Arctic Foxes, and some authorities place the latter under 
<taxonomicName id="4C0505D5BF2DFFD376A8FA5DF6D9D8EC" authorityName="Frisch" authorityYear="1775" box="[2227,2306,1485,1514]" class="Mammalia" family="Canidae" genus="Vulpes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="26" pageNumber="437" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Vulpes</taxonomicName>
. Although significant geographic variation exists among Swift Foxes, their classification into northern (hebes) and southern (
<taxonomicName id="4C0505D5BF2DFFD378A5F9D1F8DADB58" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1823" box="[1726,1793,1601,1630]" class="Mammalia" family="Canidae" genus="Canis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="26" pageNumber="437" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="velox">velox</taxonomicName>
) subspecies is probably unjustified. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
